TY  - JOUR
ID  - 40582076
VL  - 101
Y1  - 2025 Sep
T1  - The impact of multidisciplinary care on the health-related quality of life in  people with multiple sclerosis: a systematic review.
SP  - 106581
DO  - 10.1016/j.msard.2025.106581
AB  - OBJECTIVE: To summarize the evidence regarding the impact of multidisciplinary  care on health-related quality of life (HRQoL) in people with multiple sclerosis  (pwMS). METHODS: Medline, Web of Science and clinical trials.gov were searched  using 'multiple sclerosis', 'multidisciplinary care' and 'Quality of Life'.  Interventional, cross-sectional or observational studies, published between  January 2000 and September 2023 and using at least one HRQoL outcome measure were  retained. Demographics, MS- and study specific data were extracted and the risk  of bias was evaluated. RESULTS: The search yielded sixteen articles. Study  designs consisted of fourteen randomized controlled trials, one observational and  one non-randomized intervention. Researchers reported inpatient, outpatient or  home-based interventions. Two publications included cost-effectiveness analyses.  Disease specific and generic HRQoL questionnaires were used, supplementing  physical, cognitive and psychosocial outcome measures. Multidisciplinary teams  (MDTs) usually consisted of physiotherapists, nurses, psychologists and  neurologists. Most studies focused on pwMS with high disability. No studies  demonstrated an overall sustained total HRQoL improvement, although positive  changes were found within subscales focusing on psychosocial well-being.  Comparable positive trends were seen for physical, cognitive and self-efficacy  outcomes, and cost-effectiveness. CONCLUSION: Methodological heterogeneity may  have led to inconclusive evidence regarding MDTs impact on HRQoL in MS. Future  challenges entail to (i) optimize the MDT composition, (ii) standardize outcome  measures, including HRQoL, to assess the efficacy of multidisciplinary care in  MS, and considering MS subpopulations and/or symptom clusters, and (iii) to  demonstrate the cost-effectiveness of MDTs in comparison to the standard of care  in MS.
